pull_request.title: Fixes part of #5345: Implemented Reset functionality of Platform Parameters.
pull_request.body:
Fixes part of #5345:
This pull request introduces functionality to reset locally overridden platform parameters and feature flags to their server or default values, along with UI updates to support these features.

### New Functionality

#### Platform Parameters
- Added `resetPlatformParameter` method to handle resetting parameters to server/default values
- Integrated reset functionality in presenter with proper state management
- Added UI components for reset button with conditional visibility

#### Feature Flags
- Implemented parallel `resetFeatureFlag` method for boolean flags
- Added consistent reset behavior matching platform parameters
- Integrated with existing feature flag UI components

### UI Updates
- Added observable fields to manage reset button state (`isResetAvailable`, `isResetButtonActive`)
- Updated layouts to include reset sections for both platform parameters and feature flags
- Ensured consistent styling and behavior between both reset implementations

### Testing
- Added comprehensive test coverage for both platform parameters and feature flags
- Verified reset behavior persists across activity recreation
- Confirmed proper state management during reset operations

### Screen Recording
https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/381a6912-f331-45e4-a266-7e270cac12d2

Thanks, @theayushyadav11, for pushing the logic changes and attaching the screenshots and screen recording  those are very helpful. Ive taken an initial pass on the newly redesigned version. The major requests are around storing the reset values with their details to handle them properly. The current implementation is missing server sync functionality, and there are a few design-related requests as well.

Ive mostly commented on the platform parameter parts, but most of these points also apply to feature flags. I didnt comment on those separately to avoid duplication, but please make sure the changes are applied there as well. There are also a few comments from the previous review  please ensure those are addressed. During cleanup, remove all old design code parts. This might require another pass after the changes, and Ill review it fully along with the test changes included in the next push.

Regarding the reset implementation, please PTAL at this comment. Ill follow up soon with more details on requesting direction from the team by EOD.

Additionally:
* Please update the PR title and milestone title to reflect that this PR is for the dashboard redesign.
* Include the screenshots and recording in the PR description and keep them up to date so reviewers and code owners can easily refer to them.

previously attempted in CSS, but was broken, need to use nth-of-type

Filter available robots list

Include dbus modules in distribution

issue.title: v7.8.3 doesn't delete inactive wals
issue.body:
Hello, I recently found that WAL files are not getting deleted. I've read related code and it still bothers me a lot.

### Background
RocksDB version is v7.8.3. My program will have 30 RocksDB instances internally.  I'll import lots of data every night. And I know that wal/sst will be deleted whenever background Flush/Compaction finishes. So I've modified some configs:
```
Options.max_background_jobs: 64
Options.max_background_compactions: -1
Options.max_subcompactions: 64
Options.max_background_flushes: -1
```

### Phenomenon
Before we import data every night, we will mark almost all the data in RocksDB invisible and these data will be delete in custom CompactionFilter. And we will import data later. However, it seems that **ALL** wals are not deleted even after the import finishes for a long time.

Here are some evidence:
1. We'll print a log by inheriting EventListener. However the logs are not printed.
```
    void OnFileCloseFinish(const rocksdb::FileOperationInfo& info) override {
        VLOG(4) << "Closing file finished: file path is " << info.path;
    }
```
2. There are 3923 wals in 30 RocksDB instances
```
$ find . -type f -name "*.log" | wc -l
3923
$ du -ch $(find . -type f -name "*.log") | grep total
167G	total
```
3. Here is my gdb stack. There are 64 threads all blocked by the condition variable. Since `max_background_jobs` is set to 64, I guess all threads are blocked.
```
Thread 59 (Thread 0x7fb170fff700 (LWP 2920611)):
#0  futex_wait_cancelable (private=<optimized out>, expected=0, futex_word=0x7fb185e032d0) at ../sysdeps/nptl/futex-internal.h:183
#1  __pthread_cond_wait_common (abstime=0x0, clockid=0, mutex=0x7fb185e03280, cond=0x7fb185e032a8) at pthread_cond_wait.c:508
#2  __pthread_cond_wait (cond=0x7fb185e032a8, mutex=0x7fb185e03280) at pthread_cond_wait.c:647
#3  0x00007fb1f13d1e30 in std::condition_variable::wait(std::unique_lock<std::mutex>&) () from../3rd/libstdc++.so.6
#4  0x00007fb1ef1792bc in rocksdb::ThreadPoolImpl::Impl::BGThread(unsigned long) () from ../3rd/librocksdb.so.7
#5  0x00007fb1ef179663 in rocksdb::ThreadPoolImpl::Impl::BGThreadWrapper(void*) () from ../3rd/librocksdb.so.7
#6  0x00007fb1f13d7df4 in ?? () from ../3rd/libstdc++.so.6
#7  0x00007fb1f12c2609 in start_thread (arg=<optimized out>) at pthread_create.c:477
#8  0x00007fb1f11e7353 in clone () at ../sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/x86_64/clone.S:95
```

The most interesting part is that **if I do a manual Flush, all inactive wals will be deleted at once.**

After some digging, what I suspect most is the condition variable `bg_cv_`. But since that for each place we call `bg_cv_.Wait()`, there should be a log. However, I couldn't find any  related log. Another condition variable related is `log_sync_cv_`. But we didn't set the `sync` flag in any WriteOptions. It seems that we are not blocked by it.

So could anyone help me to understand what's going on here. And why a manual Flush will bypass the problem.

pull_request.title: fix: remove conflicting /static/css route that blocked user CSS files
pull_request.body:
## Summary
- Fixes static file serving issue where user CSS files in `/static/css/` were returning 404
- Removes conflicting `/static/css/{filename}` route that was intercepting requests
- Adds `static_path` parameter to `StarHTML` constructor for better usability

## Problem
StarHTML had a built-in route `/static/css/{filename}` that intercepted all requests to `/static/css/*` before the general static file serving route could handle them. This route was looking for CSS files in StarHTML's package directory (which doesn't exist), causing user files to return 404.

## Solution  
Removed the conflicting route. Now user files in `/static/css/` are correctly served by the general static file route.

## Test plan
 Added comprehensive test coverage in `test_static_path_feature.py`
 All existing tests pass
 Linting and type checking pass
